01:11:15.290 --> 01:11:18.610
I want to make sure that
we understand context here.

01:11:18.610 --> 01:11:21.380
When you do a
simulation, when you

01:11:21.380 --> 01:11:26.540
do your computational
materials research,

01:11:26.540 --> 01:11:30.110
it's not a one size
fits all kind of thing,

01:11:30.110 --> 01:11:34.670
and it's not even a one problem,
one method kind of thing.

01:11:34.670 --> 01:11:38.090
You can have one problem
with different properties

01:11:38.090 --> 01:11:40.780
that require different methods.

01:11:40.780 --> 01:11:43.510
And which is the
right method to use?

01:11:43.510 --> 01:11:45.700
Well, very often
the answer to that

01:11:45.700 --> 01:11:49.660
is whichever one is accurate
enough for the problem at hand

01:11:49.660 --> 01:11:53.140
and fastest, and
so that's where you

01:11:53.140 --> 01:11:55.700
have to know-- you have to
test and know where you sit

01:11:55.700 --> 01:11:59.060
in accuracy phase space
with a given method,

01:11:59.060 --> 01:12:00.840
and then you go ahead with it.

01:12:00.840 --> 01:12:02.840
And if you can find a
classical potential that

01:12:02.840 --> 01:12:05.450
seems to represent this
class of materials well

01:12:05.450 --> 01:12:08.730
and you can validate that it's
getting this, by all means

01:12:08.730 --> 01:12:13.600
use that because it's going to
